To create a User Flow Diagram using Mermaid.js syntax, you need to identify the key steps in the user's journey. We'll assume a simplified example of a user journey for an e-commerce website. 

Here is a sample user flow:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A(Start) --> B(Home Page)
    B --> C{Login/Register?}
    C -->|Yes| D(Login Page)
    C -->|No| E(Continue as Guest)
    D --> F(Logged In)
    E --> F
    F --> G(Product Search)
    G --> H(View Product Details)
    H --> I{Add to Cart?}
    I -->|Yes| J(Shopping Cart)
    I -->|No| G
    J --> K{Checkout?}
    K -->|Yes| L(Checkout Page)
    K -->|No| G
    L --> M{Payment Details Entered?}
    M -->|Yes| N(Order Confirmation)
    M -->|No| L
    N --> O(End)
```

This diagram includes the following key steps:
- Users start at the Home Page.
- They decide whether to log in/register or continue as a guest.
- Users can search for products and view product details.
- Users decide whether to add items to their shopping cart.
- If they go to the cart, they then decide whether to proceed to checkout.
- During checkout, they must enter payment details.
- Finally, they receive an order confirmation.

Each step is represented as a node, and decisions are represented as conditional branches in the flow. Adjust this flow according to the specific details of your project or application.